    <article class="node-82 node node-foresight-report node-promoted node-teaser clearfix" about="/content/forecasting-after-brexit" typeof="sioc:Item foaf:Document">

      <header>
                    <h2 class="node__title node-title"><a href="content/forecasting-after-brexit">Forecasting After Brexit</a></h2>
            <span property="dc:title" content="Forecasting After Brexit" class="rdf-meta element-hidden"></span>
              <p class="submitted">
                    <span property="dc:date dc:created" content="2016-09-18T10:55:43-04:00" datatype="xsd:dateTime" rel="sioc:has_creator">Submitted by <span class="username" xml:lang="" about="/users/lisa" typeof="sioc:UserAccount" property="foaf:name" datatype="">Lisa</span> on <time pubdate datetime="2016-09-18T10:55:43-04:00">Sun, 2016-09-18 10:55</time></span>        </p>
      
          </header>
  
    
    <div class="field field-name-field-summary field-type-text-long field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even"><p><strong>Abstract:</strong> The historic June 23, 2016, vote by Britons to exit the European Union (dubbed “Brexit”) surprised pundits, policy makers, and even many voters themselves. Whether the move becomes a prelude to further exits or a lesson for those favoring stronger ties with international partners is yet hard to predict, but the long-term fallout may be more worrisome than short-term disruptions. <strong>By Joergen Oerstroem Moeller.</strong></p>
</div></div></div>
  <ul class="links inline"><li class="node-readmore first last"><a href="content/forecasting-after-brexit" rel="tag" title="Forecasting After Brexit">Read more<span class="element-invisible"> about Forecasting After Brexit</span></a></li>
</ul>
  
</article>
